[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    10[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    11[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThis is the seventh recipe in Chapter 5 and the chapter's first Complex-tier recipe (four-star complexity). It introduces the recipe-specific concepts that distinguish it from the prior entity-resolution recipes (5.1 patient, 5.2 provider, 5.3 address, 5.4 eligibility, 5.5 cross-facility, 5.6 claims-clinical): name is no longer a string but a time-varying attribute with effective spans, sources, supporting documents, sensitivity classifications, and access-control envelopes; the matcher operates against a temporal-identity model rather than a flat name field; the load-bearing concern is dignity rather than data quality, with gender-affirming care, intimate-partner-violence relocation, witness-protection, and protective-custody all exercising the sensitivity-class machinery; the access-control envelope (not the matcher) is the system's primary enforcement primitive for who sees what; the historical retrofit problem (decades of records under prior names) is a one-time backfill that is a project rather than a feature; the cross-organizational propagation problem is uniquely unsolvable by the institution alone (the patient-mediated path is becoming the load-bearing pattern); and the regulatory context (21st Century Cures Act information-blocking, HIPAA, post-Dobbs and post-Bostock state-law overlays) is more directly load-bearing for compliance than in any prior recipe in the chapter.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    12[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    13[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe opening cancer-infusion-center vignette earns its position: the nurse preparing chemotherapy in chair 4 with a patient whose chart has been silently fragmented by a name change ("the chart-rendering layer in the EHR did not consult the cross-reference, or consulted it and applied it incorrectly, or consulted it and rendered the historical chart under the prior name without surfacing the linkage to the nurse, or consulted it and silently dropped the historical chart entirely") sets up the cascade of operational vignettes (women's health clinic with forty-year horizon and over-forty-percent lifetime name-change rate, gender-affirming care service line, state immunization registry, oncology service line with cumulative-anthracycline-dose continuity, Medicare-Advantage-insurance-verification with three-name-variant Medicare card, ACO HEDIS quality measurement, TEFCA QHIN identity exchange, multi-decade outcomes-research cohort refresh) at exactly the right level of "this is what longitudinal name-change matching actually looks like in production" energy. The clinical-safety stakes are correctly elevated without melodrama; the dignity-of-the-patient framing is present without being preachy; the recipe earns the four-star complexity rating it claims.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    14[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    15[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Technology section's "Why Names Are Not What You Think They Are" subsection is the chapter's clearest articulation of the temporal-identity-model versus flat-name-field mismatch. The seven-dimension enumeration of what the time-varying-name model has to capture (effective span, source, authority and document references, sensitivity classification, cross-reference linkages, sex and gender as separate time-varying fields, reversibility and superseding events) is correct and at the right grain. The six-bullet "Why It Is Harder Than It Sounds" enumeration (historical records carry only the name current at the time, supporting documents are unavailable for many name changes, family members are a strong confounder more so than in non-temporal matching, sensitivity and patient-autonomy considerations are not negotiable, cross-organizational reach magnifies every failure mode, the retrofit problem is enormous) is correct and recipe-specific. The "Where the Field Has Moved" subsection (gender-affirming care as first-class data-model concern, FHIR's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mPatient.name[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m as a list with [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140muse[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mperiod[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m fields, state-level vital-records integration variability, information-blocking obligations applying to records under prior names, equity and disparity monitoring with name-tradition cohort axes, patient-mediated identity through the CMS Patient Access API ecosystem) is correctly granular and forward-looking.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    16[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    17[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe six-stage architecture (ingest the demographic update or new record, detect a candidate name-change event, evaluate the candidate against the patient's existing identity record, persist the temporal-name update with audit and sensitivity metadata, propagate the linkage to dependent stores, react to events that supersede prior linkages) is the right shape for the problem. The trigger-source heterogeneity (registration update, payer eligibility refresh, vital-records feed, cross-organizational match refresh, document upload, patient-facing app connection, bulk historical-records reconciliation) is correctly handled by a single downstream pipeline with event-aware re-evaluation. The detection step's elevation as the load-bearing addition versus recipe 5.1 ("the temporal model needs an explicit detector because the addition of a new name to an existing identity is structurally different from a new record matching an existing identity; the indirect case is the dominant operational path and is the one that institutions tend to under-invest in") is the recipe's strongest single architectural primitive. Threshold calibration as name-change-specific (not re-using the recipe 5.1 thresholds) is correctly framed as discipline rather than convenience. Sensitivity classification at the prior-name level rather than the identity level is the right model. The split-of-concerns between the matcher (knows the linkage) and the access-control envelope (controls who sees what) is correctly elevated to architectural primitive ("the matcher is not deciding what to display; it is deciding what is true. The display decision lives in the access-control envelope, which is consulted by every consumer that reads the identity record"). Reversibility as the architecture rather than as a feature is the right framing. Document-source strength as a confidence input is correctly recipe-specific. The TransactWriteItems plus outbox pattern in Step 4 pseudocode is a positive structural improvement on the chapter pattern (5.1, 5.2, 5.3, 5.4, 5.5 all carried Finding A1 for the absence of this pattern; recipes 5.6 and 5.7 specify it).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    18[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    19[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Honest Take is the recipe's most operationally pointed section, with eleven observations earning the recipe's voice: name changes as the operational substrate rather than the exception case (the recipe's strongest single framing on this domain), the over-trusting-front-desk-asserted-changes-without-documents trap, the under-investing-in-patient-portal-flow trap, the matcher-versus-access-control-envelope split-of-concerns observation, the gender-affirming-care patient experience observation (operational rather than algorithmic), the names-from-non-dominant-culture-traditions observation (reference data is the dominant source of cohort disparity), the historical-retrofit observation (do it deliberately with patient communication and conservative thresholds), the cross-organizational propagation observation (patient-mediated flow as strategic investment), the build-the-invalidation-pipeline-first observation (matches 5.6's strongest single operational insight on its domain), the access-control-envelope-as-versioned-queryable-artifact "would do differently" observation, the audit-volume observation (sensitivity-classified events generate substantially more audit data than general ones), and the closing information-blocking-cuts-both-ways observation (the institution must release records under prior names AND honor patient preferences for prior-name suppression in disclosures, simultaneously, per-patient, per-context, per-disclosure). The Variations and Extensions section (FHIR-native temporal-name representation, patient-mediated propagation, vital-records integration, tokenization-based privacy-preserving reconciliation, gender-affirming-care workflow integration, public-health-registry-specific reconciliation, cross-organizational push notification, active-learning-driven configuration tuning, sensitivity-class-specific audit channels, audit-summary delivery to patient, multi-step name-change history with effective-date intervals, family-disambiguation rules) is well-scoped and frames each extension at the right grain.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    20[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    21[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThat said, two correctness-and-compliance gaps at HIGH severity need attention before publication, plus a recipe-specific set of MEDIUM and LOW items. (1) The architecture invokes a per-event detection and resolution Lambda, an invalidation Lambda consumed by 5.1 / 5.4 / 5.5 / 5.6 events plus document-strength-promotion events plus sensitivity-class-update events plus reversal events plus identity-merge / unmerge events plus correction events, a read API for downstream consumers (chart-rendering, release-of-information, patient-portal services, quality-measurement, care-coordination), and the cross-recipe EventBridge fan-out to nine consumers (local MPI, cross-reference table, cross-facility matcher, claims-clinical linkage, chart-rendering layer, release-of-information workflow, patient-portal services, quality and risk-adjustment pipelines, HealthLake FHIR Patient.name list); the identity-boundary checks on these paths are not specified at the architectural level. The recipe's own TODO at the IAM Permissions row names the chapter-wide pattern from 5.1 / 5.2 / 5.3 / 5.4 / 5.5 / 5.6 ("pair with scoped resource ARNs for the highest-stakes actions following the chapter pattern") but the architecture text does not actually specify the producer-signed envelope, the per-Lambda execution-role binding, or the cross-recipe event acceptance criteria. The consequence is uniquely sharp here because the patient-portal-app trigger source is patient-authenticated rather than system-authenticated (a different authentication model than any prior recipe), the vital-records feed is cross-organizational (a state agency with its own data-use agreement and its own audit posture), the document-upload trigger source carries the legal-change supporting evidence (a forged document upload could falsely promote a self-reported change to STRONG-source status), and the sensitivity-class-update path is consequential per its name (a forged update could downgrade a GENDER_AFFIRMING / WITNESS_PROTECTION / IPV_RELOCATION classification to GENERAL, retroactively widening the access-control envelope and producing dignity-and-safety failures the patient cannot recover from). (2) The cohort-stratified accuracy monitoring is invoked as "applies here too" with the cohort-distribution stakes correctly elevated in the Honest Take ("Patients with names from non-dominant-culture naming traditions experience more matcher errors. Transgender patients experience higher rates of operational friction that affect care experience even when the matcher itself is technically correct"), and the production-gaps section names the suggested values ("Cohort-stratified detection-rate disparity > 0.05 = MEDIUM alarm; cohort-stratified false-acceptance-rate disparity > 0.01 = HIGH (clinical safety implications)"), with a recipe-specific addition of "the patient-experience-and-dignity committee is an explicit reviewer for this recipe in addition to the standard analytics-governance committee"; but the architecture pattern does not specify the cohort-axis enumeration, the disparity-calculation method, the per-metric emission cadence, or the remediation pathway. Same chapter pattern as 5.1 / 5.2 / 5.3 / 5.4 / 5.5 / 5.6 Finding A2; the cohort-distribution stakes are recipe-specific because name-handling-error disparities are dignity failures that the patient experiences directly and repeatedly, not just analytic ones, and the cohort axes (name-tradition cohort, transgender-or-gender-diverse cohort, name-change-frequency cohort, age-of-name-change cohort) are recipe-specific.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    22[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    23[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mTwelve chapter-wide and recipe-specific MEDIUM patterns repeat or are recipe-new (audit-log retention floor with Object Lock specifics, three review queues with sensitivity-aware audit posture, patient-access information-blocking read path, idempotency keys per-stage with DLQ topology, threshold calibration governance, cross-recipe event contract, vital-records integration pattern, access-control-envelope versioning and query API, multi-step name-change history reasoning, sex-and-gender-data-model coordination, document-strength-promotion handling and effective-date adjustment, audit-volume storage tier and per-class retention floor for sensitivity classes). Most are explicitly TODO'd or named in the Honest Take and production-gaps section; this review carries them forward at MEDIUM severity reflecting the chapter editor's eventual consolidation responsibility.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    24[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    25[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mVoice is excellent. Em dash count: 0 (verified by searching for U+2014 codepoints in the file; zero matches). En dash count: 0 (verified the same way for U+2013; zero matches). The 70/30 vendor balance is maintained: AWS service names appear first in the AWS Implementation section after The Problem, The Technology, and General Architecture Pattern have been specified vendor-agnostically. CC voice is consistent throughout: the opening cancer-infusion-center vignette, the eight you-are-running-X scenarios that ground the operational landscape (women's health clinic forty-year horizon, gender-affirming care academic medical center, state immunization registry, oncology service line cumulative-anthracycline-dose, Medicare Advantage insurance verification with three name variants on the Medicare card, ACO HEDIS quality measurement, TEFCA QHIN, multi-decade outcomes research cohort refresh), the Honest Take's "Names change. People get married. People get divorced. People get remarried" cadence, the closing information-blocking-cuts-both-ways line, the engineer-explaining-something-cool register exactly. Parenthetical asides land well ("a refugee with a reconstructed identity" as the rare-DOB-instability case is the recipe's strongest single parenthetical aside on the temporal-identity-model). Clinical and regulatory accuracy is strong (cumulative-anthracycline-dose tracking is the correct cardiotoxicity-relevant exposure variable; HEDIS measures with multi-year lookback windows is the correct ACO context; TEFCA QHIN identity exchange is correctly framed; FHIR HumanName [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140muse[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mperiod[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m fields are correctly specified; CMS Patient Access API and Patient-Facing-App ecosystem framing is correctly granular; 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions are correctly elevated; 42 CFR Part 2 implications for substance-use-treatment records are not directly mentioned but the recipe's sensitivity-class machinery accommodates them; post-Dobbs reproductive-health-care state-law overlays and post-Bostock employment-context implications are correctly named in the BAA-and-Trust-Framework TODO).[K
