[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    202[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Honest Take's closing line: "the information-blocking obligation cuts both ways. The institution is obligated to release a patient's records on request, including records under prior names, but the patient also has the right to constrain how her prior names are referenced in disclosures. The release pipeline has to honor both obligations simultaneously, and the resolution between them is per-patient, per-context, per-disclosure. Build the release pipeline with the access-control envelope in scope from day one, not as a retrofit. The architecture is then load-bearing for compliance and for patient dignity in the same operational layer, which is the right place for both." Why-This-Isn't-Production-Ready / Information-blocking-compliance paragraph: "Build the patient-access-API release path as a deliberate workflow that consults both the linkage and the envelope, with audit logging on every release." The TODO at line 1365 explicitly names the chapter-pattern fix.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    203[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe correctly elevates the 21st-Century-Cures-Act information-blocking compliance posture to "load-bearing for compliance" and elevates the dual-obligation framing (release records under prior names AND honor patient preferences for prior-name suppression) but does not architect the patient-access read path. Four concrete gaps:[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    204[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    205[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m1[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe patient-access read path is not in the architecture diagram.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The architecture diagram shows the cross-recipe EventBridge fan-out to nine consumers but does not show the patient-access-report path (likely an API Gateway plus Lambda authorizer plus a separate Lake Formation grant scope plus the authentication path through the institution's patient portal).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    206[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    207[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m2[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe dual-obligation enforcement at the read path is not specified.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe correctly identifies that the institution must simultaneously release records under prior names (information-blocking compliance) AND honor patient preferences for prior-name suppression in disclosures (patient-dignity compliance). The Lambda handler at the patient-access read path has to consult both the linkage (the matcher's job) and the access-control envelope (the dignity-compliance enforcement). Without architectural specification, implementations either over-release (exposing prior names that the patient preferred to suppress) or under-release (failing to include records under prior names, which is increasingly characterized as information blocking). The architecture should specify the read-path Lambda's responsibility for both obligations.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    208[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    209[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m3[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe provider-access read path is also not architected.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Under the 21st Century Cures Act, providers requesting records as part of treatment have a similar access right; the architecture should specify this read path alongside patient-access. Provider-access is more permissive than patient-access in some respects (the treatment-relationship grant may permit prior-name disclosures that the patient-access scope would not) and more constrained in others (the provider-access scope is bounded by the treatment relationship, with audit on every prior-name access).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    210[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    211[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m4[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe release-of-information workflow audit posture is not specified.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Every prior-name disclosure should be logged with the access-control-envelope state at the time of disclosure, the disclosure scope, the requesting principal's identity, the rationale, and (for sensitivity-classified prior names) the patient's notification per the audit-summary-delivery feature. Without this, the institution cannot defend a release-of-information decision to a regulator and cannot honor the audit-summary-delivery feature for sensitivity-classified patients.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    212[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    213[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add a patient-access-and-provider-access read path to the architecture diagram and the architecture pattern: [38;2;180;142;173m*[38;2;180;142;173m"Patient-access and provider-access read paths run through API Gateway with the institution's patient-portal authentication or provider-directory authentication, respectively. The Lambda authorizer binds the requesting principal to the identity_id (patient-access) or to the treatment-relationship (provider-access). The Lambda handler retrieves the identity record's linkage (the matcher's view of which records belong to this patient regardless of name), applies the access-control envelope (the dignity-compliance enforcement determining which prior names are released and which are suppressed), retrieves the relevant clinical records under all linked names, and returns the response with explicit handling of prior-name disclosures. The audit log records every patient-access and provider-access read with the access-control-envelope state at the time of disclosure, the disclosure scope, the requesting principal, the rationale, and the linked patient-portal-audit-summary-delivery state. Compliance with the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions is enforced at this read path simultaneously with patient-dignity compliance; the dual-obligation enforcement is the read-path Lambda's defining responsibility. Same pattern as recipe 5.5, recipe 5.6 with the recipe-specific dual-obligation elevation."[38;2;180;142;173m*[K
